import java.io.*;
import java.net.*;

public class java_42523_SocketServer_A01 {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        ServerSocket welcomeServer = new ServerSocket (8189); // create server socket on port 8072 for client connection using listen to the same address and port we used when connected. We are listening from any IP of our own machine not just localhost or other machines in network segment, then forwarding that message back
        while(true){  	// infinite loop till break statement is hit/executed 	until server socket receive a client connection request it won't do anything until the accept method call by using listen to get connected clients. In this case we are not actually handling or accepting any data from an incoming stream of bytes, just waiting for connections
            Socket connectionSocket = welcomeServer .accept(); // Accepts incomming socket requests and returns a new socket object representing network input/output channels on the specified port 8072. It waits until another client connects to this server’s IP address or its specific remote host name from which it can accept an incoming connection request
            DataInputStream dis =new DataInputStream (connectionSocket .getInputStream());	// get data stream inputs and instantiate a new inputstream object using the socket'd bytes 	to read through datagram packets, inbound streams are always available for reading at any moment of time. The client program can then send information to this server
            OutputStream outToClient = connectionSocket .getOutputStream();	// get output stream and instantiate a new instance with sockets network ports where you would like the data read from inputstreams sent back via an Internet protocol socket (TCP/IP) into. 	This is also called sending information to other client'
            System.out.println("Received: " + dis .readUTF());	// this should print out whatever message was received by a specific connected customer on the server’ console, it can then send back data based upon needs in real-world application or just return any text as example here we are simply echoing messages that come from client
            String userInput = "Hello Client"; // Set up default input string for sending to clients 	we want a message sent at some point. This is what the server will now send back when it receives such data, so you can see how this part works in real world application too as we are just echoing and returning same inputs
            outToClient .writeUTF (userInput); // write user input string into output stream to client’s socket 	send information from here onwards. We use datagram packets for sending data which is more efficient than TCP/IP sockets when the message length isn't too big or else it might exceed buffer size
            connectionSocket .close();	// After done with communication, close this out stream and inputstream to clean up resources before moving onto another client’s request. 	This will be a good practice so that we are not consuming memory unnecessarily in case of long running socket connections or if the same message is sent repeatedly
        }   // end while loop till break statement executed (if server runs infinite then it keeps on accepting requests)   			// and processing them, otherwise your program goes into an endless block with no exit. 	For example a simple echo application in Java Socket Programming where socket programming for reading message is the only functionality of this sample code
        welcomeServer .close(); // close server once done using it to make sure all resources are freed up and stop accepting new connection requests, as per our previous explanation we can see here. 	Just keep note that you should not leave any resource unclosed in Java/Swing applications like main or other threads unless your application is going into a loop where the client connections will continue for life until manually stopped by user input
    }   // end of server side code (main method) which listens on socket port 8189. Once connected, it waits to receive message from Client and sends back same response with echoing functionality in real world application or just return any text as example here we are simply returning the received input
}   	// main function ends  	and this will run forever until manually stopped by user using command 'ctrl + c' on console for above code. 	The server is now listening to client requests and sending back a response, which can then be used in real world applications as echo application or similar functionality here we are not doing anything complex with it only returning same input